<section>
  <title>And, or &amp; not</title>

  <slide><title>Negation</title>
  <p>
    Given <m>P</m> we can form a new statement with the opposite truth value.
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>
      It is not the case that <m>P</m>
    </p>
  </blockquote>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>negation</term> of a statement <m>P</m> is denoted <m>\neg P</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>When <m>P</m> is <em>true</em>, the negation <m>\neg P</m> is <em>false</em>.</li>
          <li>When <m>P</m> is <em>false</em>, the negation <m>\neg P</m> is <em>true</em>.</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        The negation is also denoted <m>!P</m> and <m>\lnot P</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  </slide>

  <slide><title>Examples and a table</title>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>The negation of <q>It is tuesday</q> is <q>It is <em>not</em> Tuesday</q></li>
      <li>The negation of <q><m>4 \in A</m></q> is <q><m>4 \not\in A</m></q></li>
      <li>The negation of <q>4 is even</q> is <q>4 is not even</q> or better <q>4 is odd</q>.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    We can summarise what negation does to truth values via a <term>truth table</term>
  </p>
  <sidebyside>
  <tabular  left="minor" right="minor" top="minor" bottom="minor" halign="center">
    <row>
      <cell><m>P</m></cell><cell><m>\neg P</m></cell><cell><m>\neg(\neg P)</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</sidebyside>

<p>
  Note
<ul>
  <li>the <term>double negation</term> of <m>P</m> has the same truth value as <m>P</m></li>
  <li>the <term>law of the excluded middle</term>: exactly one of <m>P</m> or <m>(\neg P)</m> is true.</li>
</ul>
</p>
</slide>

<slide><title>Conjunction, and, disjunction, &amp; or</title>
  <p>
    We combine statements using <term>and</term> &amp; <term>or</term> to make new statements.
  </p>
  <p>
    The words <q>and</q>, <q>or</q> have precise mathematical meanings
  </p>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let
        <m>P</m>
        and
        <m>Q</m>
        be statements.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
            The <term>disjunction</term> of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is
            <q> <m>P</m> <term>or</term> <m>Q</m> </q> and is denoted <m>P \lor Q</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>P\lor  Q</m> is true when at least one of <m>P,Q</m> is true, else false.
          </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
            The <term>conjunction</term> of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is
            <q> <m>P</m> <term>and</term> <m>Q</m> </q> and is denoted <m>P \land Q</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>P\land  Q</m> is true when both <m>P,Q</m> are true, else false.
          </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Note: <em>colloquial</em> use of <q>or</q> is often different from this <em>mathematical</em> <q>or</q>
  </p>

</slide>

<slide><title>Examples and tables</title>
<p>
  Let <m>P</m> be <q>8 is even</q> and let <m>Q</m> be <q>15 is prime</q>, then
  <ul>
    <li><m>P \lor Q</m> is <q>8 is even or 15 is prime</q></li>
    <li><m>P \land Q</m> is <q>8 is even and 15 is prime</q></li>
  </ul>
  The first is true since <m>P</m> is true, the second is false since <m>Q</m> is false.
</p>
<p>
  A truth table helps summarise:
