<slide><title>Inclusive and exclusive</title>
<p>
  Mathematical <q>or</q>or is <term>inclusive</term> <mdash /> <m>P \lor Q</m> is true when <em>at least one</em> statement is true.
</p>
<p>
  Colloquial <q>or</q> is often <term>exclusive</term> <mdash /> <m>P \;\mathrm{xor}\; Q</m> is true when <em>exactly one</em> statement is true.
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Would you like chicken or beef for dinner?</p>
</blockquote>

<sidebyside>
  <tabular>
    <row>
    <cell><m>P</m></cell>
    <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
    <cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell>
    <cell><m>P \; \mathrm{xor}\; Q</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell><term>F</term></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</sidebyside>
<p>
  For exclusive-or write <q>Exactly one of <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m></q> or <q><m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> but not both</q>.
</p>
